The {{ill|Ōnishi clan|ja|大西氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} originated from the {{ill|Kondō clan|ja|近藤氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, sent from {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都|qq=draft|qq=draft}} as estate stewards (shōkan) during the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. After settling in Awa and changing their family name, they served the {{ill|Ogasawara clan|ja|小笠原氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who were appointed as governors during the rule of {{ill|Ogasawara Nagakiyo|ja|小笠原長清|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. By the {{ill|Nanboku-chō period|ja|南北朝時代 (日本)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the Ōnishi and Ogasawara clans fought for the Southern Court, but when the tide turned, the Ogasawara allied with the {{ill|Hosokawa clan|ja|細川氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and departed, leaving the Ōnishi clan independent. By the Sengoku period, the Ōnishi had become the dominant power in western Awa.

Ōnishi Kakuyō's father, Yorifusa, married a sister of {{ill|Miyoshi Nagayoshi|ja|三好長慶|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, while Kakuyō himself married a daughter of {{ill|Miyoshi Jikkyū|ja|三好実休|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, cementing strong ties with the {{ill|Miyoshi clan|ja|三好氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. From his base at {{ill|Hakuchi Castle|ja|白地城|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Kakuyō controlled the borderlands of Awa, {{ill|Sanuki Province|ja|讃岐国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Iyo Province|ja|伊予国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

As the Miyoshi clan's influence in Awa waned and the {{ill|Chōsokabe clan|ja|長宗我部氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} rose in {{ill|Tosa Province|ja|土佐国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Hakuchi Castle became a key target for {{ill|Chōsokabe Motochika|ja|長宗我部元親|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who sought to unify Shikoku. Initially, Kakuyō sent his younger brother, Yorikazu, as a hostage to Motochika, agreeing to a truce. However, when the Miyoshi sought {{ill|Oda clan|ja|織田氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} support and took a more aggressive stance, Kakuyō broke the truce and prepared for war.

In response, Motochika swiftly defeated the Miyoshi forces in Awa and attacked Hakuchi Castle's satellite fortifications. In {{ill|Tenshō|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 5 (1577), he captured {{ill|Tao Castle|ja|田尾城|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in just two days, forcing Kakuyō to flee to {{ill|Masanuki Castle|ja|麻城|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Sanuki. The following year, Masanuki Castle fell, and Kakuyō surrendered on the advice of Yorikazu, who had been treated favorably by Motochika.

Returning to Awa, Kakuyō sought refuge with his son-in-law, Shigekiyo Nagamasa, the lord of {{ill|Shigekiyo Castle|ja|重清城|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. When Nagamasa refused Kakuyō's call to surrender to the Chōsokabe, Kakuyō betrayed him and orchestrated his assassination. Motochika then entrusted Shigekiyo Castle to Kakuyō, but shortly afterward, Kakuyō was defeated and killed in a counterattack by {{ill|Sogō Masayasu|ja|十河存保|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a Miyoshi ally.

