As the Miyoshi clan's influence in Awa waned and the {{ill|Chōsokabe clan|ja|長宗我部氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōsokabe clan|qq=}} rose in {{ill|Tosa Province|ja|土佐国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tosa Province|qq=}}, Hakuchi Castle became a key target for {{ill|Chōsokabe Motochika|ja|長宗我部元親|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōsokabe Motochika|qq=}}, who sought to unify Shikoku. Initially, Kakuyō sent his younger brother, Yorikazu, as a hostage to Motochika, agreeing to a truce. However, when the Miyoshi sought {{ill|Oda clan|ja|織田氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oda clan|qq=}} support and took a more aggressive stance, Kakuyō broke the truce and prepared for war.

In response, Motochika swiftly defeated the Miyoshi forces in Awa and attacked Hakuchi Castle's satellite fortifications. In {{ill|Tenshō|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō (Momoyama period)|qq=}} 5 (1577), he captured {{ill|Tao Castle|ja|田尾城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tao Castle|qq=}} in just two days, forcing Kakuyō to flee to {{ill|Masanuki Castle|ja|麻城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Masanuki Castle|qq=}} in Sanuki. The following year, Masanuki Castle fell, and Kakuyō surrendered on the advice of Yorikazu, who had been treated favorably by Motochika.

Returning to Awa, Kakuyō sought refuge with his son-in-law, Shigekiyo Nagamasa, the lord of {{ill|Shigekiyo Castle|ja|重清城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shigekiyo Castle|qq=}}. When Nagamasa refused Kakuyō's call to surrender to the Chōsokabe, Kakuyō betrayed him and orchestrated his assassination. Motochika then entrusted Shigekiyo Castle to Kakuyō, but shortly afterward, Kakuyō was defeated and killed in a counterattack by {{ill|Sogō Masayasu|ja|十河存保|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sogō Masayasu|qq=}}, a Miyoshi ally.

